Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Properties", "Subsection",
 CellID->544617716,ExpressionUUID->"65de7320-23c1-4a97-a24e-4e1944055afd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "It is worth noticing that the physical interpretations of classical joint \
and conditional entropies defy our expectation when applied to the quantum \
joint and conditional entropies. For example, unlike the solid inequality ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"H", "(", "X", ")"}], "\[LessEqual]", 
    RowBox[{"H", "(", 
     RowBox[{"X", ",", "Y"}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a9ae1534-1798-436f-a131-fb0b17c242ce"],
 " for classical random variables ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["X", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a838714f-f460-46db-bbda-84385529c22b"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["Y", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ef0d22ec-5f47-47a8-8d48-7a1027fff289"],
 " , the analogous inequality ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", "A", ")"}], "\[LessEqual]", 
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ",", "B"}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9574be6f-3705-4031-9961-04c1f51e0dfe"],
 " does not hold. Equivalently, the conditional entropy is not necessarily \
positive, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", "|", "B"}], ")"}], " ", "\[NotGreaterEqual]", " ", "0"}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"3ec4d5fb-49f1-4cb5-9d03-dcf548aa051f"],
 "; hence, the the data compression inequality ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"H", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"X", ":", "Y"}], ")"}]}], "\[LessSlantEqual]", " ", 
    RowBox[{"H", 
     RowBox[{"(", "X", ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1a453e38-d88e-4dba-9638-bf0601a8c335"],
 " is not generalized to quantum information, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ":", "B"}], ")"}], "\[NotLessEqual]", 
    RowBox[{"S", "(", "A", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d5a4d4d6-cebf-44a0-95ff-3a465c12478f"],
 " nor ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ":", "B"}], ")"}], "\[NotLessEqual]", 
    RowBox[{"S", "(", "B", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "dfa6ed06-2c29-4ea6-b549-0052d8e11f2d"],
 ". Such violations are usually attributed to quantum entanglement, a special \
kind of correlation between subsystems (see the tutorial \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]",
 ButtonBox["Entanglement and Entropy",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/EntanglementAndEntropy"],
 "\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] for more details). For example, consider the \
quantum state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      TemplateBox[{"00"},
       "Ket"], "+", 
      TemplateBox[{"11"},
       "Ket"]}], ")"}], "/", 
    SqrtBox["2"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8f133e74-d136-401e-9486-41e1d15adad5"],
 ". It is a pure state and certainly ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ",", "B"}], ")"}], "=", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"6a40004f-3f49-441f-83b8-98a79c23665b"],
 ". However, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["\[Rho]", "A"], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Rho]", "B"], "=", 
     RowBox[{"I", "/", "2"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "160eb1fa-918c-423b-86c3-082f4ad85b8f"],
 " and hence ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", "A", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"S", "(", "B", ")"}], "=", 
     RowBox[{"1", ">", " ", 
      RowBox[{"S", "(", 
       RowBox[{"A", ",", "B"}], ")"}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5bc691c4-a998-4800-9c19-7649d0dbf367"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1143999714,ExpressionUUID->"56a50e74-de9e-4f27-b06d-f2cb7c8da9f9"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Nevertheless, the quantum mutual information is always non-negative. It \
leads to the ",
 StyleBox["subadditivity",
  FontSlant->"Italic"]
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->960081030,ExpressionUUID->"fc03fd6c-af0e-4327-9530-8a1f27a9f974"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     SubscriptBox["\[Rho]", 
      RowBox[{"A", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "B"}]], ")"}], "\[LessEqual]", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"S", "(", 
      SubscriptBox["\[Rho]", "A"], ")"}], "+", 
     RowBox[{"S", "(", 
      SubscriptBox["\[Rho]", "B"], ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"57da652a-c402-4494-8e3c-d68678974ac1"],
 " ."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1217551190,ExpressionUUID->"661cdac8-e0f4-405c-8459-be17274d851a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This can be easily seen by employing Klein\[CloseCurlyQuote]s inequality \
(see Problem 7.5 of the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    Cell[
     TextData["Quantum Workbook"]], 
    "https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-91214-7"},
   "WebLink",
   BaseStyle->{"TechNoteText"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8e7c08e3-de37-407b-a9ac-b330050e6147"],
 ")."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1586045173,ExpressionUUID->"dadb7d44-33bd-499c-9bcc-26f3016b49c1"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The subadditivity further implies an interesting property of the von \
Neumann entropy. Introduce a third system ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["C", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "92cbeafe-4cc1-4a99-9eb9-5d30aa827de8"],
 ", and consider a purification ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    TemplateBox[{"\[CapitalPsi]"},
     "Ket"], 
    RowBox[{"A", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "B", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "C"}]], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"85d3844c-5682-46e1-82f4-6fd42d7af6c3"],
 " of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Rho]", 
    RowBox[{"A", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "B"}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "cb5ee785-3a28-4cd8-8003-f0a6381c2d37"],
 " into ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", "A"], "\[CircleTimes]", 
    SubscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", "B"], "\[CircleTimes]", 
    SubscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", "C"]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"7e71d0d0-3741-477b-a5ec-367e1bb596e4"],
 ". We employ the subadditivity inequality to get"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1457353133,ExpressionUUID->"40f1c74e-6ec4-495b-9313-ebe902c7be57"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ",", "C"}], ")"}], "\[LessEqual]", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"S", "(", "A", ")"}], "+", 
     RowBox[{"S", "(", "C", ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a6fd722c-3772-4d78-9c14-f5543e0c4c66"],
 " ."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1248915310,ExpressionUUID->"a8c229fb-1e03-462e-999e-71fab833063c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Since ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    TemplateBox[{"\[CapitalPsi]"},
     "Ket"], 
    RowBox[{"A", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "B", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "C"}]], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"6bdc2bfa-ce94-467d-808e-7b514275171f"],
 " is a pure state,"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->867028796,ExpressionUUID->"99c46b93-fe69-40c3-93f9-2a36113f6fbb"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ",", "B"}], ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"S", "(", "C", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9fda1558-c9bc-488b-b2f7-5128a14cc19f"],
 " ,     ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ",", "C"}], ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"S", "(", "B", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e0781b94-2b09-4124-bccd-f723373e8520"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1090488228,ExpressionUUID->"9490f68a-3f81-4ef0-84d2-7da06ad07119"],

Cell["Therefore, it follows that", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1074744205,ExpressionUUID->"86d0b209-d07e-4f32-80fe-ff8e27fd259c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"S", "(", "B", ")"}], "-", 
     RowBox[{"S", "(", "A", ")"}]}], "\[LessEqual]", 
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ",", "B"}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b6faa2f3-11b5-4d6d-97a3-4c0c991d3929"],
 " ."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1140192669,ExpressionUUID->"75cd8a32-e0a4-47ba-b1fa-42d5da9f949d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Similarly, from ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"B", ",", "C"}], ")"}], "\[LessEqual]", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"S", "(", "B", ")"}], "+", 
     RowBox[{"S", "(", "C", ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a66de4b0-d6d9-4fda-ace8-02ddb2239bb5"],
 ", we have"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1938548539,ExpressionUUID->"523dd6d0-e62d-4d38-baa7-de9bdc4e65a6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"S", "(", "A", ")"}], "-", 
     RowBox[{"S", "(", "B", ")"}]}], "\[LessEqual]", 
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ",", "B"}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c387f850-14cb-49ff-9759-775da8c436b3"],
 " ."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1910098602,ExpressionUUID->"827a7ea6-3335-4e19-ae2e-efdf3e0f591d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Combining the above two inequalities, we have the so-called ",
 StyleBox["triangle inequality",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " for the von Neumann entropy"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1370777330,ExpressionUUID->"ab9d47c3-0919-4d2c-b1e1-d72789526751"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"S", "(", 
       SubscriptBox["\[Rho]", "A"], ")"}], "-", 
      RowBox[{"S", "(", 
       SubscriptBox["\[Rho]", "B"], ")"}]}], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], "\[LessEqual]", 
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     SubscriptBox["\[Rho]", 
      RowBox[{"A", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "B"}]], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"5f54696f-4e24-46bb-a03f-fa6f6eb3a086"],
 " ."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1049858610,ExpressionUUID->"c1c7d7a8-2670-4b7e-b216-b78ed2dd5f38"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "There are many more interesting and useful properties of the quantum joint \
and conditional entropies and mutual information. Here, we have discussed a \
minimal set of them. Interested readers are referred to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    Cell[
     TextData["Wehrl (1978)"]], "https://doi.org/10.1103/RevModPhys.50.221"},
   "WebLink",
   BaseStyle->{"TechNoteText"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9db9675b-b4b8-498b-bf53-fe926c01773f"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1161753077,ExpressionUUID->"9d8e929c-1192-4ccd-8618-2b5c6fb1b41d"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Quantum Entanglement", "Subsection",
 CellID->984311748,ExpressionUUID->"38276352-9954-4be5-9645-fc9cf0302e3e"],

Cell["\<\
Recalling that the quantum mutual information characterizes the correlation \
between subsystems, it is frequently used to examine the extent of quantum \
entanglement. Indeed, for pure states, the quantum mutual information equals \
to twice the entanglement entropy, and provides as good an entanglement \
measure as the entanglement entropy. For mixed states, however, the quantum \
mutual information is not a rigorous entanglement measure because the quantum \
mutual information specifies not only quantum correlation (such as \
entanglement) but also classical correlation. A classic example is a mixed \
state of the form\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1902468969,ExpressionUUID->"1e180ab9-e80d-4fc9-b83e-56a02d75be71"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["\[Rho]", "AB"], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     FractionBox["1", "2"], 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{
        TemplateBox[{"00"},
         "Ket"], 
        TemplateBox[{"00"},
         "Bra"]}], "+", 
       RowBox[{
        TemplateBox[{"11"},
         "Ket"], 
        TemplateBox[{"11"},
         "Bra"]}]}], ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9b90d297-a3da-4923-84cc-1927d202110a"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->555378433,ExpressionUUID->"cae97136-22cb-4145-87d6-a0dfb2ddbfde"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Being a classical mixture of two separable states, this state is clearly a \
separable state, and any reasonable entanglement measure (such as the ",
 ButtonBox["logarithmic negativity",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/ref/LogarithmicNegativity"],
 " discussed above) must vanish for this state. However, due to the classical \
correlation contribution, the quantum mutual information of this state is \
finite, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"S", "(", 
     RowBox[{"A", ":", "B"}], ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"log2", "\[NotEqual]", "0"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d2f279c2-c8bf-43af-bd52-4dac89623472"],
 ". Nevertheless, since the quantum mutual information capture quantum \
correlation and is relatively easy to calculate, it is still commonly used to \
investigate quantum entanglement quantitatively in practical cases."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1704779553,ExpressionUUID->"f642909c-8695-4e0b-9fff-54628118427e"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

